What is FPGA?
Field‑Programmable Gate Arrays are integrated circuits that consist of an array of programmable logic blocks, configurable interconnects, and embedded hard IP (such as high‑speed transceivers, memory controllers, and DSP engines). Unlike fixed‑function ASICs, an FPGA can be programmed and re‑programmed throughout its lifecycle, allowing designers to tailor the hardware to specific workloads, implement custom accelerators, and perform iterative development cycles with dramatically reduced time‑to‑market. This flexibility is especially critical for emerging domains-AI‑driven edge inference, 5G base‑station signal processing, and autonomous‑vehicle sensor fusion-where algorithmic changes are frequent and hardware must keep pace.
